<topic xml:id="ha-testing-resource-failover"
 role="task" xml:lang="en"
 xmlns="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" version="5.2"
 xmlns:its="http://www.w3.org/2005/11/its"
 xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
 xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"
 xmlns:trans="http://docbook.org/ns/transclusion">
  <info>
    <title>Testing resource failover</title>
    <meta name="maintainer" content="tahlia.richardson@suse.com" its:translate="no"/>
    <abstract>
      <para>
        This procedure checks if the cluster moves the virtual IP address to another node if
        the node that currently runs the resource is set to <literal>standby</literal>.
      </para>
    </abstract>
  </info>
  <procedure>
    <step>
      <para>
        Open a terminal and ping your virtual IP address:
      </para>
<screen>&prompt.user;<command>ping &subnetI;.10</command></screen>
    </step>
    <step>
      <para>
        Log in to &hawk;.
      </para>
    </step>
    <step>
      <para>
        Under <menuchoice><guimenu>Status</guimenu><guimenu>Resources</guimenu></menuchoice>,
        check which node the virtual IP address (resource <systemitem>admin_addr</systemitem>)
        is running on. This procedure assumes the resource is running on
        <systemitem class="server">&node1;</systemitem>.
      </para>
    </step>
    <step>
      <para>
        Put <systemitem class="server">&node1;</systemitem> into <guimenu>Standby</guimenu> mode.
      </para>
     <!-- Use "crm node standby NODE" instead? -->
    </step>
    <step>
      <para>
        Click <menuchoice><guimenu>Status</guimenu><guimenu>Resources</guimenu></menuchoice>.
        The resource <systemitem>admin_addr</systemitem> should have migrated to
        <systemitem class="server">&node2;</systemitem>.
      </para>
    </step>
  </procedure>
  <para>
    During the migration, you should see an uninterrupted flow of pings to the virtual IP
    address. This shows that the cluster setup and the floating IP work correctly. Cancel the
    <command>ping</command> command with <keycombo><keycap function="control"/><keycap>C</keycap></keycombo>.
  </para>
</topic>
